{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648187"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:52:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:52:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18301"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18301"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78519"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11019"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18301"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26896"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78519"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe popliteal fossa is a diamond-shaped space located at the back of the knee joint. It is an important anatomical region containing several neurovascular structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a content of the popliteal fossa?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior tibial artery","Femoral artery","Great saphenous vein","Saphenous nerve","Tibial nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the major contents of the popliteal fossa. It is a branch of the sciatic nerve and runs through the popliteal fossa to supply the posterior compartment of the leg and the sole of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E is not located in the popliteal fossa; it is found in the anterior thigh and becomes the popliteal artery after passing through the adductor hiatus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esaphenous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the femoral nerve and runs along the medial aspect of the leg, but it does not pass through the popliteal fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior tibial artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the popliteal artery but it does not reside in the popliteal fossa; it travels anteriorly to supply the anterior compartment of the leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreat saphenous vein\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial vein that runs along the medial aspect of the leg and thigh, but it does not pass through the popliteal fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The popliteal fossa contains important neurovascular structures including the tibial nerve, common peroneal nerve, popliteal artery, and popliteal vein.","Understanding the anatomy of the popliteal fossa is crucial for clinical assessments and surgical procedures involving the knee and lower leg."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy 